  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Preface to the Presentation of the Great Code of Governance
  author: Choi Hang
  language: eng
  text: |-
    When the sage orders all under heaven, he must await the accumulation of virtue through a hundred years. When the king adapts to the times, he establishes precedents for ten thousand generations. Thus does the setting of this Great Code befit this auspicious age.

    I humbly reflect: governance through the Way remains constant, yet statecraft transforms with the customs of the people. In establishing the state and ordering the lands, the Zhou divided authority among six ministers, while the Han, to eliminate excess and remove harshness, bound itself to three simple laws. Both achieved lasting transmission through apt implementation.

    Our sacred court receives the luminous mandate. Brilliant rulers succeed one another, expanding the patterns of a hundred dynasties. The laws are now fully established, creating new institutions for this age. Yet the compilation suffered from excess detail, and those who must enforce it despair at its profusion.

    His Majesty Hye-jang, both sage and divine, combines civil and martial virtues. He swept away treachery and brought peace to the realm, enduring countless hardships while riding the six dragons of heaven. His accomplishments shine brilliantly; his ordered governance flows with clarity. Change is necessary; we cannot merely inherit the past. Thus we gathered the old records and consulted the new ordinances. All was examined against precedent; all decisions flowed from the royal wisdom. We stripped away the trivial and grasped the essential, using simplicity to govern complexity, creating a code unbreakable by time.

    Sacred reverence deepens daily; wise governance brings order. The foundation of law must be rightly laid and never forgotten. The sovereign himself oversees the beginning of all matters, making the compilation of the six classics the urgent priority. Extracting the essentials, carrying forward the predecessors' will, adapting to present needs and deep harmony with the people's voice—this is the true charter for governing the realm, not merely guiding the people to righteousness.

    We, humble and unworthy, have presumed to assist in this compilation, laboring day and night with little to show. The heavens and earth have their weave; we merely receive instruction. Let this be reviewed and its observance commanded. Let all who come after heed it without fail. Let them honor the wisdom passed down, making the established constitution a mirror without flaw, thereby preserving and glorifying this great enterprise.
  footnotes:
    - The 'six ministers' (육경) refers to the administrative structure of the Zhou dynasty, representing the highest level of government organization.
    - The 'three laws' (삼장) of the Han dynasty were a simplified legal code known for its restraint and effectiveness.
    - The 'six dragons' (육룡) is a traditional metaphor for imperial power and the conduct of celestial governance.
    - The 'six classics' (육전) refers to the foundational texts and legal codes that form the basis of statecraft.
